#answer[]

#answer[
  From lectures, we know that the first 32-bit number will be loaded into the Stack Pointer register `sp`, and the second 32-bit number into the Program Counter `pc`. 
  
  The stack is the machanism that we use to store local variables in functions, and in later lectures we learn that `sp` is initialised to the highest memory address in RAM. From the memory map that we saw in lectures, we know that this address is `0x20004000`. In `.hex` files, numbers are stored in the "little-endian" format, which means that the end of the number (least significant bytes) are stored at the end of the sequence. This is why the number is displayed as `00 40 00 20`, keeping in mind that a byte consists of two hexadecimal numbers.

  The second word number will be sent to the program counter. This effectively executes a branch instruction, jumping into a new subroutine. To find out which function we jump into, we need to find the function located at the address indicated by `dd 06 00 00`, which (translating from little-endian) is the value `0x000006dd` (this may be different when you compile). We firstly note something odd about this number. It's an odd number (`0xd = 13`)! An instruction cannot be at this location, since instructions are two bytes long, and are stored one after the other. In my disassembly (see @lst:disassembly-func-later), we find the function `__reset` at address `0x06dc`, and this _is_ where the CPU jumps to. What explains this difference? It is the convention that when the CPU jumps to an odd address, that it switches to executing the 16-bit Thumb instructions, rather than the 32-bit native ARM instructions (as discussed in lectures). The Cortex-M0 can only execute these Thumb instructions, but we still need to follow this convention for compatibility with larger ARM chips.

  The selection of `__reset` as the first function that the CPU jumps to, is done by placing the address of the function in the 2nd field of the `__vectors` array in `startup.c`.
]

