#answer[
#set enum(numbering: "a)")
+ No, function names are not needed to run the code. These are useful to _humans_, and are used in C code to make it easy for _humans_ to remember what re-usable pieces of code (i.e. subroutines) are for. When the compiler produces byte code, these subroutines are given an address in memory, and this is all that an branch instruction needs to jump to a new subroutine.
+ The `arm-none-eabi-objcopy` program will remove this unnecessary information, and just leave the instructions. This will ultimately determine the exact sequence of binary that is written to the Flash memory on the micro:bit. This is good, so we don't waste valuable program space (we only have 256KB!) on data that only matters to humans, and not to running the acutal program. However, it does mean, that the `.hex` file is lacking the helpful information that is displayed in the disassembler. In fact, when the disassembler is presented with just a sequence of hexadecimal numbers, it doesn't even know how to interpet it! It could be Native ARM code, where the instructions are all 32 bits long, or Thumb code, where they are 16 bits long! The byte code could be interpreted in both ways, and both sequences of instructions can be run... Although only one will run according to the intentions of the original programmer. However, since the assembler is faced with two possible interpretations of the machine code, and it has no way of knowing what hte intentions of the original programmer were, it cannot determine how to proceed, and we get an error.
+ RTFM (Read the Fantastic Manual)
+ The first 8 bytes still encode the highest memory address in RAM, followed by the address of the `__reset` function that should be run on startup. However, we now see this data displayed not just as a sequence of numbers as before, but instead interpreted as instructions. This is because the information that this `.vectors` section is just binary data is _not_ stored in the `.hex` file, and the disassembler just chooses to interpret this as instructions. It is up to _us_ as engineers (or... reverse-engineers) to know that the ARM CPU interprets these numbers _not_ as instructions, but instead as values for the Stack Pointer and Program Counter. So the instructions that are displayed are the correct decodings of the machine code, but they will never be executed as instructions. And so I would say that they don't "make sense".
]
